Plastic debris is one of the most visible consequences of the human impact on the environment. However, the magnitude of the problem is still unclear. The origin of the solar system is one of the most important questions in astronomy. We determined the ages of 40 large silicon carbide grains extracted from the Murchison CM2 meteorite. The grains have ages of 3.9 ± 1.6 Ma to ∼3 ± 2 Ga before the start of the Solar System ∼4.6 Ga ago. This is the oldest age of a presolar grain so far. The grains were part of aggregates in the interstellar medium. The grains acquired the bulk of their cosmogenic nuclides in the interstellar medium and not by exposure to an enhanced particle flux of the early active sun. This result has important implications for the origin of the solar system.

We provide a comprehensive picture of the evolution of the global fishing fleet, its fishing effort, and the effective catch per unit of effort. This paper describes the COVIDcast API, a data source that provides open access to a wide range of COVID-19 surveillance signals. The data are available in a common format through the API and accompanying R and Python software packages. The Northwest Forest Plan (NWFP) was a landmark policy for the conservation of biodiversity in the United States. We show that the NWFP has not been successful in reversing the decline of older-forest–associated bird populations. We also show that the early-seral ecosystem, which is the focus of the recently proposed restoration of the NWFP, is not declining. However, the early-seral ecosystem is declining in two ecoregions, the Coast Range and Cascades, and bird populations are declining in these ecoregions. These findings underscore the importance of continuing to prioritize older forests under the NWFP and ensuring that the recently proposed creation of early-seral ecosystems does not impede the conservation and development of older-forest structure.

Entanglement and thermodynamics are two of the most fundamental concepts in physics. They are also the key ingredients for the emergence of classical and quantum phase transitions. However, the interplay between them is still poorly understood. Here, we show that the entanglement dynamics in integrable systems can be fully described in terms of quasiparticles, which are the elementary excitations of the system. The biomass of the biosphere is a key quantity for understanding the structure and dynamics of the biosphere. However, a global, quantitative view of how the biomass of different taxa compare with one another is still lacking. Here, we assemble the overall biomass composition of the biosphere, establishing a census of the ≈550 Gt C of biomass distributed among all of the kingdoms of life. We show that the biomass of humans is an order of magnitude higher than that of all wild mammals combined, and that the biomass of animals is mainly concentrated in the ocean. Finally, we highlight the historical impact of humanity on the global biomass of prominent taxa, including mammals, fish, and plants. Our results provide a global view of the biomass composition of the biosphere and can be used to understand the structure and dynamics of the biosphere.

Aerosols are one of the most important factors in the climate system. However, the impact of aerosols on clouds is still a controversial topic. This is mainly due to the lack of simultaneous observations of aerosols and clouds. Here, we introduce a new instrument, the dual-FOV high-spectral-resolution lidar, to observe aerosols and clouds simultaneously. This instrument is expected to be a significant contributor to the investigation of aerosol–cloud interaction. We demonstrate the capability of this instrument by observing aerosols and clouds over Beijing. The results show that the aerosol loading has no discernible effect on the liquid water path, but increased droplet number concentration and decreased droplet effective radius. This finding supports the hypothesis that aerosol-induced cloud water increase caused by suppressed rain formation can be canceled out by enhanced evaporation. Thus, these observations obtained from the dual-FOV HSRL constitute substantial and significant additions to understanding ACI. This technique is expected to represent a significant step forward in characterizing ACI.

This work examined the relationship between men’s and women’s endorsement of the culturally idealized form of masculinity—hegemonic masculinity (HM)—and support for Donald Trump, the 45th president of the United States. Consistent with our theoretical backdrop, HM predicted voting for and evaluations of Trump, over and above political party affiliation, gender, race, and education. These effects held when controlling for respondents’ trust in the government, in contrast to a populist explanation of support for Trump. HM was associated with less trust in the government, more sexism, more racism, and more xenophobia but continued to predict unique variance in evaluations of Trump when controlling for each of these factors. The findings highlight the importance of psychological examinations of masculinity as a cultural ideology to understand how men’s and women’s endorsement of HM legitimizes patriarchal dominance and reinforces gender, race, and class-based hierarchies via candidate support. These findings have implications for understanding the political climate in the United States and the world.

This study shows that the management of annual cropping systems on Mollisols can be modified to increase soil organic carbon storage. Our results show that the addition of legumes and manure, and the integration of perennial pastures into annual cropping systems can increase soil organic carbon storage. These results have important implications for the climate-smart agriculture movement, which aims to increase agricultural productivity while reducing greenhouse gas emissions. Our results suggest that the management of annual cropping systems on Mollisols can be modified to increase soil organic carbon storage, and that the integration of perennial pastures into annual cropping systems can be a key strategy for increasing soil C. This approach can help to mitigate the impacts of climate change and improve the sustainability of agricultural production systems.

We introduce a computer vision method to measure changes in the physical appearances of neighborhoods from time-series street-level imagery. We connect changes in the physical appearance of five US cities with economic and demographic data and find three factors that predict neighborhood improvement. First, neighborhoods that are densely populated by college-educated adults are more likely to experience physical improvements—an observation that is compatible with the economic literature linking human capital and local success. Second, neighborhoods with better initial appearances experience, on average, larger positive improvements—an observation that is consistent with “tipping” theories of urban change. Third, neighborhood improvement correlates positively with physical proximity to the central business district and to other physically attractive neighborhoods—an observation that is consistent with the “invasion” theories of urban sociology. Together, our results provide support for three classical theories of urban change and illustrate the value of using computer vision methods and street-level imagery to understand the physical dynamics of cities. Our work is a step toward a more complete understanding of the physical dynamics of cities.

We consider repeated games with tail-measurable payoffs, i.e., when the payoffs depend only on what happens in the long run. The proof relies on techniques from stochastic games and from alternating-move games with Borel-measurable payoffs.

COVID-19 has resulted in a staggering death toll in the United States. We estimate that the pandemic has resulted in a reduction in life expectancy at birth of 1.13 y, lower than any year since 2003. We also project a 0.87-y reduction in life expectancy at age 65 y, both of which are several times the 0.68-y reduction for Whites. These projections imply an increase of nearly 40% in the Black−White life expectancy gap, from 3.6 y to over 5 y, thereby eliminating progress made in reducing this differential since 2006. Latinos, who have consistently experienced lower mortality than Whites (a phenomenon known as the Latino or Hispanic paradox), would see their more than 3-y survival advantage reduced to less than 1 y.

Crop experts are the eyes and ears of the agricultural community, and their assessments are critical to monitor crop status and predict crop yields. However, the information provided by crop experts is subjective and categorical, and is not easily amenable to quantitative analysis. We propose a method to convert the original categorical data into a continuous probabilistic variable that is better suited to quantitative analysis. We show that the resulting model is robust across different crops, exhibits long-term stability, and has nation-wide validity. We demonstrate that the proposed model can be used to monitor crop status and provide earlier and more precise predictions of crop yields than official USDA forecasts released midseason. Our findings have implications for the development of agricultural monitoring systems and for the understanding of the dynamics of agricultural production.

This study provides a unique perspective on the role of anthropogenic climate change in the occurrence of a drought that threatened the water supply of a city. We show that anthropogenic climate change increased the likelihood of the 2015–2017 rainfall deficit by a factor of five to six. The probability of such an event will increase from 0.7 to 25% by the year 2100 under an intermediate-emission scenario (Shared Socioeconomic Pathway 2-4.5) and to 80% under a high-emission scenario (Shared Socioeconomic Pathway 5-8.5). These results highlight the strong sensitivity of the drought risk in SSA to future anthropogenic emissions. This work is expected to be of interest to the general public, water managers, and policymakers.

Autism is a complex disorder with a genetic basis. However, the genetic basis of autism is so complicated that it is difficult to identify the causal paths that lead to the core autistic symptoms. Here, we show that behavioral flexibility, which is a measure of behavioral plasticity, is a converging target of the autism-risk genes. This finding provides a framework for understanding the genetic basis of autism and for identifying the causal paths. This study also provides a model system for studying the genetic basis of behavioral plasticity. (Show more)

We present a 2D photonic crystal system for interacting with cold cesium (Cs) atoms. The band structures of the photonic crystals are predicted to produce unconventional atom–light interaction behaviors, including anisotropic emission, suppressed spontaneous decay, and photon-mediated atom–atom interactions controlled by the position of the atomic array relative to the photonic crystal. This study is the first to estimate the climate-change–driven acceleration of global mean sea level over the last 25 y. The results are consistent with the IPCC AR5 model projections, and the results are robust to the choice of satellite altimeter data, the choice of climate model, and the choice of sea level trend.

Pain is a major public health problem, and the number of Americans reporting pain is rising. However, the elderly are reporting less pain than those in midlife. This is the mystery of American pain. We show that the elderly are not less pain-prone than those in midlife, but rather that the prevalence of pain has been increasing for each successive birth cohort of the less educated. This pattern is not explained by changes in occupation or levels of obesity. If this trend continues, tomorrow’s elderly will be sicker than today’s elderly, with potentially serious implications for healthcare.

This paper provides a comprehensive analysis of the effects of vote-by-mail on electoral outcomes. We use a difference-in-differences design to estimate the causal effect of vote-by-mail on turnout, vote share, and overall turnout rates. We find that vote-by-mail does not appear to affect either party’s share of turnout, does not appear to increase either party’s vote share, and modestly increases overall average turnout rates. These findings support the conventional wisdom of election administration experts and contradict many popular claims in the media. Our findings are important for understanding the effects of vote-by-mail and for informing the ongoing debate on the future of election administration in the United States.

We live in an era of big data. This is a boon for science, but it also creates new challenges. In this paper, we describe a new challenge that arises in the context of complex statistical modeling. We call it “selective inference.” We illustrate the challenge with three examples: forward stepwise regression, the lasso, and principal components analysis. We hope that our work will help scientists to better understand the strengths and limitations of their data and models. This will help them to make better use of big data in their research. It will also help the public to understand the results of scientific research.

Wildfires are a natural part of the ecosystem, but the economic and ecological costs of wildfire in the United States have risen substantially in recent decades. We show that humans have vastly expanded the spatial and seasonal “fire niche” in the coterminous United States, accounting for 84% of all wildfires and 44% of total area burned. Human-started wildfires disproportionally occurred where fuel moisture was higher than lightning-started fires, thereby helping expand the geographic and seasonal niche of wildfire. Actions to raise awareness and increase management in regions prone to human-started wildfires should be a focus of United States policy to reduce fire risk and associated hazards.

We introduce a computer vision method to measure changes in the physical appearances of neighborhoods from time-series street-level imagery. We connect changes in the physical appearance of five US cities with economic and demographic data and find three factors that predict neighborhood improvement. First, neighborhoods that are densely populated by college-educated adults are more likely to experience physical improvements—an observation that is compatible with the economic literature linking human capital and local success. Second, neighborhoods with better initial appearances experience, on average, larger positive improvements—an observation that is consistent with “tipping” theories of urban change. Third, neighborhood improvement correlates positively with physical proximity to the central business district and to other physically attractive neighborhoods—an observation that is consistent with the “invasion” theories of urban sociology. Together, our results provide support for three classical theories of urban change and illustrate the value of using computer vision methods and street-level imagery to understand the physical dynamics of cities. Our work is a step toward a more complete understanding of the physical dynamics of cities.

Freshwater fisheries are a critical source of food, recreation, and livelihoods, but their importance is often overlooked. We provide a global map of riverine fisheries, which reveals that 90% of the world’s catch comes from river basins with above-average stress levels. Our data also show that freshwater fisheries provide the equivalent of all dietary animal protein for 158 million people, and that poor and undernourished populations are particularly reliant on inland fisheries. However, intensive fishing in regions where rivers are already degraded by other stressors may undermine efforts to conserve biodiversity. This syndrome of poverty, nutritional deficiency, fishery dependence, and extrinsic threats to biodiverse river ecosystems underscores the high stakes for improving fishery management. Our data can facilitate the inclusion of inland fisheries in environmental planning to protect both food security and species diversity.

We are always communicating with others, and we do so in a variety of ways. We can speak, we can write, we can use our faces and bodies, and we can use our minds. But how do we know when two people are communicating in a way that is meaningful to each other? We show that the speed at which people respond to each other is a robust predictor of whether two people feel connected to each other. This finding suggests that the speed of communication is a fundamental signal of connection.

Language is a highly complex system that involves the integration of information over time. Here we propose a computational model of memory in the brain that is based on the adaptive changes in the excitability of neurons. This mechanism is sensitive to the context of the stimulus and can be used to bind information over time. We show that this mechanism can be used to bind linguistic features over time, which is critical for the processing of language. This work provides a step toward a computational neurobiology of language.

This study is the first of its kind to examine the nutrient inputs from all tributaries of a large lake. We found that the nutrient loads from small tributaries were high for their size, and that the bioavailability of nutrients from small watersheds was higher than expected. These findings have important implications for coastal eutrophication, as well as for the management of nutrient inputs to large water bodies.

This study is the first to evaluate the impact of certification on deforestation in oil palm plantations in Indonesia. We find that certification reduced deforestation by 33% from a counterfactual of 9.8 to 6.6% y−1. However, certification had no causal impact on forest loss in peatlands or active fire detection rates. Broader adoption of certification in forested regions, strict requirements to avoid all peat, and routine monitoring of clearly defined forest cover loss in certified and RSPO member-held plantations appear necessary if the RSPO is to yield conservation and climate benefits from reductions in tropical deforestation.
